AllLife Credit Card Customer Segmentation¶

Background:¶

AllLife Bank wants to focus on its credit card customer base in the next financial year. They have been advised by their marketing research team, that the penetration in the market can be improved.
Based on this input, the Marketing team proposes to run personalized campaigns to target new customers as well as up sell to existing customers. Another insight from the market research was that the customers perceive the support services of the bank poorly. Based on this, the Operations team wants to upgrade the service delivery model, to ensure that customers queries are resolved faster. Head of Marketing and Head of Delivery both decide to reach out to the Data Science team for help.

Objective:¶

To identify different segments in the existing customer based on their spending patterns as well as past interaction with the bank.

Key Questions:¶

  1. How many different segments of customers are there?
  2. How are these segments different from each other?
  3. What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?

Data Description:¶

Data is of various customers of a bank with their credit limit, the total number of credit cards the customer has, and different channels through which customer has contacted the bank for any queries, different channels include visiting the bank, online and through a call centre.

Deliverable – 2: Insights from graphs (5 marks)¶

Properly comment on the codes, provide explanations of the steps taken in the notebook and conclude your insights from the graphs.

2.1 Insights from the graphs

  1. The variables are in different scales. So scaling is needed for unsupervised learning
  2. Checking the Mode indicates that some customer keys are repeated. These are not duplicate in the true sense because the other values are different.
  3. The credit limit of the repeated customer key is checked and the rows with higher credit limit is retained assuming that there was an credit limit increase for these customer.
  4. Observing the KDE in the histogram indicates that the Agv_credit_limit and Total_visits_online are right skewed and may have outliers. So outliers treatment will be considering in data pre-processing
  5. The Histogram shows that all the variables are not normally distributed.
  6. Plotting boxplot shows that the Avg_credit_limit and the Total_visits_online have outliers. Outliers treatment for these two columns may be considered during pre-processing.
  7. Since there are very few outliers in the Total_visits_online outliers treatment will be considered. We are not considering outliers treatment for Avg_credit_limit because the outliers are larger in number and will change the shape of the data if treated.
  8. The heatmap shows that there is a strong positive correlation between the credit limit and number of credit cards held by a customer
  9. The heatmap also tells us that online visitors tend to have more credit limit.
  10. There is a strong negative correlation between the number of calls and the credit card held by customer and number of calls and average credit limit. This may imply the the poor customer service faced by customers with more credit cards.
  11. Communication based mode of contact (Phone call or Online) shows a negative correlation with the direct visit to bank.
  12. Pair plot between variables indicates somewhat linear relationship between average credit limit and total credit cards, between online visits and average credit limit, between total credit cards and total online visits
    13.Looking at the diagonal of the pair plot indicates that there may be at least 4 peaks amongst the data set which would imply the cluster value to be at least 3 or 4.
  13. Data transformation may be also contemplated to treat skewness of data.
  14. Dimensionality reduction may not be needed with the dataset

3.1.1 K-Means clustering of scaled only dataset

In [523]:
# elbow method to find the optimal K for clustering on scaled only dataset
distortion =[] # within cluster variance 
K = range(1,10) # k ranges for the elbow method

for k in K:
    kmeanModel = KMeans(n_clusters=k) # initiating KMeans algorithm
    kmeanModel.fit(dfScaled) # fit model to the scaled dataset
    distortion.append(kmeanModel.inertia_)# append within cluster variance value

# plot elbow 
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
plt.plot(K,distortion,'bx-')
plt.xlabel('K')
plt.ylabel('Distortion')
plt.title('The Elbow Method showing optimal K')
plt.show();

The Elbow method indicated that there are three (3) clusters

3.1.2 K-Means clustering of outliers treated, transformed and scaled dataset

In [530]:
# elbow method to find the optimal K for clustering on pre-processed dataset
distortion =[] # within cluster variance 
K = range(1,10) # k ranges for the elbow method

for k in K:
    kmeanModel = KMeans(n_clusters=k) # initiating KMeans algorithm
    kmeanModel.fit(dfTransformed) # fit model to the scaled dataset
    distortion.append(kmeanModel.inertia_)# append within cluster variance value

# plot elbow 
plt.figure(figsize=(10,6))
plt.plot(K,distortion,'bx-')
plt.xlabel('K')
plt.ylabel('Distortion')
plt.title('The Elbow Method showing optimal K')
plt.show();

The Elbow method indicated that there are three (3) clusters

7.3 Answers to Key questions

7.3.1 How many different segments of customers are there?

There are three(3) segments of customers for the bank based on the data available for analysis

7.3.2 How are these segments different from each other?

Cluster 0 - has customers with average(medium) credit card limit, number of credit cards and calls to the bank. But they visit the bank more frequently but visit online the least. One explanation could be that these customer may not be the most tech savvy customer group.

Cluster 1 - has customers with least credit card limit and credit cards, but these customer have the highest calls to the bank and have average visits to the bank or online. Looking at the trends of this group, it seems that this is the group that approaches the bank for support services the most because their queries aren't resolved faster.

The lower number of credit cards and credit limit would indicate this to be a grieved group with respect to the services provided by the bank.

Cluster 2 - has customers with highest credit card limit and number of credit cards. This would indicate that the group is tech savvy and has less grievances with the bank.

7.3.3 What are your recommendations to the bank on how to better market to and service these customers?

Marketing strategy to target new customers and upsell to existing customers

Assuming that all cluster groups have equal probability of approval for credit products, Clusters-0 and Cluster-1 are potential customer base for upselling to existing customers and attracting new customers if the new customers fall in these clusters

1. Online Campaigns

Online campaigns should be primarily targeted to Cluster-1 as the customers of this group have very low credit limit and credit cards but have average online presence.

Cluster-2 can also be targeted for online campaigns as the customers of this group have the highest online visits but this group may lead to increased False Positives because their credit limit is the highest and the group may be saturated and not accept any new products/services/offers.Also, the number of customers belonging to this group are also small.

2. Offline Campaigns/in-person campaigns

Cluster-0 should be primarily targeted for offline campaigns as the customers of this group visit the bank often. Cluster-1 can also be considered for offline Campaigns based on their bank visit history.

3. Improving support services

Cluster-1 seems to be the group with the most grievance assuming that the contacts made by them to the bank via phone, online and in-person visits is for support services. The operations team should contact Cluster-1 group for considering their feedback for improving the support services and retaining the customer base.
